<dl id="n08181i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08181i">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08181i"> 181(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font><span class="strike"><span class="striketext">s</span></span> broth<font color="green">[er]</font><font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> Dathi lightning in Alps</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In 404 Niall of the Nine Hostages was killed in the English Channel on board his own ship. His successor, Dathi, ruled nearly three years and then died in Gaul, struck by lightning when on a raiding expedition&mdash;according to the chroniclers, as far inland as the Alps. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 16</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Niall N&oacute;igiallach died in 406 in the English channel whilst engaged in a marauding expedition. Niall&apos;s nephew Dathi succeeded, and was the last king of pagan Ireland. According to the old legend, he was struck dead by a flash of lightning at the foot of the Alps in 428, after he had wantonly destroyed the cell of a holy hermit named Parmenius. </mm> </dd></dl>
